03913nam a22005295i 9780300157338DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20122012ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001573387 a10.12987/97803001573382doi  a(DE-B1597)486216  a(OCoLC)777950800  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aPOE0050102bisacsh04a811/.522231 aStein, Gertrude, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStanzas in Meditation :bThe Corrected Edition /cGertrude Stein; Emily Setina, Susannah Hollister. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tOn Not Not Reading Stanzas in Meditation -- tThe Turning Point -- tThe Impossible: Gertrude Stein -- tStanzas in Meditation -- tAppendix A. Publication History -- tAppendix B. Reading Text -- tAppendix C. Editorial Practices -- tAppendix D. Notes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1950s, Yale University Press published a number of Gertrude Stein's posthumous works, among them her incomparable Stanzas in Meditation. Since that time, scholars have discovered that Stein's poem exists in several versions: a manuscript that Stein wrote and two typescripts that her partner Alice B. Toklas prepared. Toklas's work on the second typescript changed the poem when, enraged upon detecting in it references to a former lover, she not only adjusted the typescript but insisted that Stein make revisions in the original manuscript.This edition of Stanzas in Meditation is the first to confront the complicated story of its composition and revision. Through meticulous archival work, the editors present a reliable reading text of Stein's original manuscript, as well as an appendix with the textual variants among the poem's several versions. This record of Stein's multi-layered revisions enables readers to engage more fully with the author's radically experimental poem and also to detect the literary impact of Stein's relationship with Toklas. The editors' preface and poet Joan Retallack's introduction offer insight into the complexities of reading Stein's poetry and the innovative modes of reading that her works require and generate. Students and admirers of Stein will welcome this illuminating new contribution to Stein's oeuvre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aPOETRY / American / General.2bisacsh1 aHollister, Susannah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRetallack, Joan1 aSetina, Emily, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300157338423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300157338.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles